            <p>&#34;The Jewish Messenger&#44;&#34;¬ù<lb/>
                92 Walker Street.<lb/></p>
            <p>New York Jan 2 1880.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Friend&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>Please tell your son that<lb/> I forgot to notice his book this week&#44; but<lb/> shall <hi rend="underline">not</hi> forget the coming week.<lb/></p>
            <p>As you will see from this<lb/> year&#39;s prospectus&#44; I have decided to<lb/> withdraw Hebraica as a monthly<lb/> supplement &#38; leave the field clear<lb/> for the rabbi then Review.  I shall<lb/> publish a weekly column of Hebraica<lb/> as before&#44; in larger type.<lb/></p>
            <p>I know you are busy &#38;<lb/> we are not going to ask you to<lb/> contribute anything that requires<lb/> study &#38; research&#44; but I would like<lb/> an occasional chat&#44; say a<lb/> column long&#44; in same topic of the<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>day&#44; or any other subject you<lb/> please&#8212;in a light style&#44;<lb/> for our readers between ages<lb/> of 18 &#38; 25&#44; a class who<lb/> are not interested in distinctively<lb/> religious editorials&#44; but must be<lb/> attracted by light food.  Short<lb/> sermonettes&#44; crisp&#44; &#38; fresh&#44; would<lb/> be readable.  You can sign them or<lb/> not&#44; as you prefer.<lb/></p>
            <p>I think your son will make<lb/> a good venture with his book.  Only<lb/> bid him be careful with proofs &#38;<lb/> leave nothing to printer&#39;s proof&#45;<lb/>reader.<lb/></p>
            <p>With best wishes&#44;<lb/>
                Yours&#44;<lb/>
                		A. S. Isaacs.<lb/></p>
            <p>I call your attention to<lb/>
                an item &#34;First&#45;Fruits&#34;¬ù in our<lb/> 
                locals this week.  It is a little<lb/> 
                idyl from the life of every&#45;day&#44;<lb/>
                &#38; <hi rend="underline">so</hi> encouraging<lb/></p>
        </body>
